text: Argument suggests Court will invalidate DOMA, but entirely possible a majority won't agree on legal rationale.
author: JanCBS

text: KAGAN, deeply skeptical, quotes '96 House report on DOMA, says it raises "red flag" Congress was "affected by "dislike, fear, animus."
author: JanCBS

text: SOTOMAYOR also asks about federalism: "What gives fed govt right to be concerned at all abt what definition of marriage is?"
author: JanCBS

text: Kennedy cares deeply about federalism issues (more than Robts). Tells atty defending DOMA marriage "always considered a state police power."
author: JanCBS

text: While Court indicates DOMA unconstitutional, justices suggest different rationales--equal protection (liberals) and federalism (Kennedy).
author: JanCBS

text: KENNEDY, the key swing vote, on federalism: "Question is whether the federal govt under our fed scheme has authority to regulate marriage?"
author: JanCBS

text: But issue of jurisdiction in DOMA -- and whether Court can decide case -- is a serious one. Several justices expressed reservations.
author: JanCBS

text: Today's arguments suggest federal Defense of Marriage Act in jeopardy. Five justices imply law is unconstitutional.
author: JanCBS

text: True, this. Much can happen btwn args & opinion. MT @Robertwaldeck: Never known what majority thinks from oral args, even cases I've tried.

text: A punt on standing? Majority clearly not ready for broad ruling ok'ing sex marriage--but also seem dissatisfied w options for narrow one.
author: JanCBS

text: Justices on both sides also dubious of Obama Admin argument for a narrow ruling that states w civil unions can't ban same sex marriage.

text: KAGAN highly skeptical of Prop 8, asked atty defending it: What harm do you see happening--and when and how--to institution of marriage?

text: ALITO: asked about "need to be cautious" .."Same sex marriage is very new...newer than cell phones or the internet."
